ce:section.ce:para:
A mechanism is proposed to illustrate the solid-state fluorescence emission (Figure 6
                        ). On the one hand, the doping of F atoms into CDs exerts a strong segmentation effect on the sp2-hybridized structures within the CDs, leading to the formation of numerous defects around the CDs. Concurrently, the creation of these defects is accompanied by the generation of excitons. Due to the strong electron-withdrawing ability of F atoms, charges preferentially accumulate around these defects. The recombination of excitons at these defect sites results in new fluorescence emissions, thereby suppressing the ACQ effect and achieving solid-state emission.
                           36
